The Royal London Hospital is home to one of the largest children’s hospitals in the UK with one of London's busiest paediatric accident and emergency departments.

It is also home to London’s Air Ambulance service and one of the capital's leading trauma and emergency care centres and hyper-acute stroke centres.

The Breathe London Node is located near the entrance to A&E to assess the exposure of visitors, patients and staff at the hospital. This Node was deactivated on 14th December 2024 at the end of GLA funding for operation.  Monitoring may recommence at this location at a later date.

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
North Middlesex University Hospital has been serving the community for over a century. The first hospital buildings on the present site were built in 1909.

The hospital has expanded and modernised over the years, improving the medical, surgical, stroke and children’s services including a brand new maternity and neonatal unit. The new maternity unit is equipped with with state-of-the-art facilities and is among the best NHS maternity units in the country.

The Breathe London Node is located by the front entrance and serves to assess the exposure of visitors, patients and staff at the hospital. This Node was deactivated on 14th December 2024 at the end of GLA funding for operation.  Monitoring may recommence at this location at a later date.

Newham University Hospital serves one of the most diverse populations in England. The hospital cares for more than 500 patients in its A&E department every day and is home to one of the largest maternity units in the UK with more than 6,000 births each year.

The hospital's state-of-the-art Rainbow Centre is geared up to meet the needs of its young patients and their families in a child-friendly environment. 

The Breathe London Node is located on a flag pole by the entrance to the A&E department where patients are picked up and dropped off. This Node was deactivated on 14th December 2024 at the end of GLA funding for operation.  Monitoring may recommence at this location at a later date.

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
Whipps Cross Hospital has a strong reputation as a centre of excellence for various specialist services, including urology, ENT, audiology, cardiology, colorectal surgery, cancer care and acute stroke care.

Thanks to £6.7m in funding from Barts Charity, the hospital is making a series of improvements to its Maternity and Neonatal services to improve the environment and prepare for an increase in birth rates in its local population. This will include a dedicated clinical research hub for women's services.

The Breathe London Node is located by the main entrance near the car park to assess exposure for staff, patients and visitors. This Node was deactivated on 14th December 2024 at the end of GLA funding for operation.  Monitoring may recommence at this location at a later date.

The Royal Marsden Hospital opened in 1851 as the world’s first hospital dedicated to cancer diagnosis, treatment, research and education.

Today it operates as a specialist cancer hospital and National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) Biomedical Research Centre for Cancer, working closely with its principal academic partner, the Institute of Cancer Research (ICR).

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
Established in 1828 by William Marsden, the Royal Free's founding principle was that they would take in anyone who needed treatment – the first hospital in London to do so and the only London hospital to stay open during the 19th-century cholera epidemics.

In the 21st century, the hospital continues to lead improvements in healthcare and is proud to have some of the best clinical outcomes in the country.

The Breathe London Node is located in the busy pick-up and drop-off area by the entrance assessing exposure of staff, visitors and patients. This Node was deactivated on 14th December 2024 at the end of GLA funding for operation.  Monitoring may recommence at this location at a later date.

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
Great Ormond Street Hospital is an international centre of excellence in child healthcare. It's mission is to put the ‘child first and always’.

Since its formation in 1852, the hospital has been dedicated to children’s healthcare and to finding new and better ways to treat childhood illnesses.

The Breathe London Node is located by the main entrance which receives 237,908 outpatient visits and 43,218 inpatient visits every year.

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
Air pollution is a serious issue, which  affects all of us, whether foetus, child, adult and elderly.
In the autumn 2021 a group of locals got together and created a community group 'Clean Air Bayswater’  to find a way to reduce the air pollution levels in our area.
We applied for and were very pleased  to be granted a Breathe London air pollution monitor, which will enable us to track and address air pollution in our local area.
We have developed a 12 month local community campaign to raise awareness among residents, businesses, schools and GPs of air pollution and how it impacts our health, irrespective of our age. This will involve a school education programme,  community events for residents and local business engagement activities.
Our aim is to improve the air we breathe by asking everyone living or working in Bayswater to join in, and take some simple steps to reduce air pollution in our area.  We are looking to work with other clean air groups to collaborate and share learning, so that we can all make as big a difference as possible.
We will also be looking for Westminster City Council to take action to support our campaign and actively reduce key issues such as idling.  
We believe that together we can make a difference.   Air pollution affects our lungs, heart and brains. We need to take action now. There is no excuse - The Clean Air Bayswater Group
breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.OtherTags: Clean Air Bayswater, Deployed, Mains1, V2, Westminster

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
Healthy Streets North Tottenham are a group of local residents striving for better, less polluted streets. We came together in 2020 to tackle the dominance that through-traffic has on our neighbourhood.

The rise in traffic has had a disproportionate effect on North Tottenham and the people who live here. Every day, residents experience 5000 vehicles passing their homes, which severely impacts our health, safety, lifestyle, social connections and ability to build a strong community. 

By harnessing the air quality data captured by this node, we hope to be able to persuade decision-makers at Haringey Council to take action on the ill effects of traffic pollution and implement changes which work for and benefit local residents. It will also help to raise awareness within the community and encourage others to tackle air pollution in North Tottenham.
breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.OtherTags: Community Programme, Deployed, Haringey, Healthy Streets North Tottenham, Solar300, V2

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
Victoria Park Harriers and Tower Hamlets Athletics Club is based at St. Augustine’s Hall in the north-east corner of Victoria Park in Tower Hamlets, London. It was formed in 2001 as a merger of Victoria Park Harriers (founded in 1926) and Tower Hamlets Athletics Club (founded in 1976). The club is open to all regardless of ability from the age of 9 upwards and coached training sessions occur at St. Augustine’s Hall, Mile End Stadium and the London Marathon Community Track at least twice a week. The active membership of approximately 450 athletes includes track, field, road and cross-country athletes, from beginners to Olympians. The club reflects the diversity of East London and has close links to local schools through our junior athletes.

While Mile End Stadium and the London Marathon Community Track are both over 50 metres away from busy roads and thus classified as urban background locations, St. Augustine’s Hall is about 20 metres from the A106, close to the junction with the A12, which results in poor air quality, as reported by the Breathe GB campaign, which found that St. Augustine’s Hall had the worst air quality of any sports facility in England with an average of 67 µg/m3 of NO2 and 17 µg/m3 of PM2.5 in 2018.

The Club is looking forward to using the data from the Breathe London node, which will improve the ability of Club members and local residents to avoid high pollution episodes and provide them with the data necessary to advocate for measures to improve local air quality.
breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.OtherTags: Community Programme, Deployed, Mains300, Replacement, Tower Hamlets, V2, Victoria Park Harriers

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription: This monitor was secured by Woodford Green resident Lydia Fraser-Ward to measure the levels of air pollutants in Elmhurst Gardens, E18. After spending two years visiting the park every day with her toddler, she became increasingly concerned about the air quality in the children’s playground and the effect it could be having on her son’s health. This area of the park backs onto the North Circular / A406 where it meets a major interchange with the M11 at the Charlie Brown’s Roundabout. After weeks of research she found that there were no air monitors provided by the local authority in the nearby vicinity, and that there was very limited data recorded specifically in parks and play areas relating to air pollution. Lydia joined clean air campaign group Mums for Lungs and reached out to a number of community groups, schools, environmental projects and parents in the local area to raise awareness about this issue. With their support she put together a short film to apply to the Breathe London Community Programme for this air quality node. The data will be used to inform whether further mitigation measures are needed to protect park and playground users from the motorway’s toxic air.

Although it enjoys the wildlife, biodiversity and picturesque setting that this green space provides, it is also situated on a busy road which runs under the M11 situated close by. Mums for Lungs Redbridge - a grassroots organisation made up of local residents all connected by a shared concern about air quality - was keen to work with the school to monitor levels of localised pollution coming from traffic on nearby roads and how this may be affecting the outdoor play areas of the school. 
 
Our group actively campaigns throughout the London Borough of Redbridge for more air quality monitoring in outdoor play areas and gyms, whilst also supporting parents to set up School Streets and raises awareness of the risks of idling car engines and wood burning. This monitor was secured by Woodford Green resident Rachel Southern in partnership with Mums for Lungs Redbridge Coordinator Lydia Fraser-Ward. The data from this Breathe London node will be used to inform the school and local residents of levels of nitrogen dioxide and particulate matter in the area. This information will be highly valuable and will inform whether further mitigation measures are needed to reduce air pollution levels around the school, whilst raising awareness more generally with parents about air quality in the neighbourhood.

About the group

REACH (Residents Environmental Action on Climate and Health) is a sub group of the Hampstead Garden Suburb (HGS) Residents association with a number of key stated aims including ;
•        To support Suburb residents in preparation for environmental challenges by taking initiatives that will play a part in reducing our contribution to emissions and thus to the warming of the planet 
•        Consider actions we can take to reduce local pollution and enhance biodiversity.
•        Consult and co-operate with LB Barnet, HGS Trust, City of London, Transport for London, Environment Agency, and other relevant bodies as applicable.
•        Aim is to achieve Net Zero greenhouse gas emissions from the area by 2040 and to work with residents and relevant stakeholders to achieve this ambitious target.
Node location 

One key area of concern that REACH has identified within HGS is air quality (AQ) as the Suburb is bordered and dissected by some of London’s busiest roads, including the A40, the A1, East End Road and the Finchley Road. The lack of meaningful AQ data within the suburb means we can’t take steps to identify and address the root cause (whether it is vehicles, buildings, or wood burners), educate residents and inform change in HGS and the wider area. There is, perhaps, a preconception that there is no AQ problem in the suburb because it is indeed founded on the Garden City principles of open green spaces. However. Whilst there is an obvious impact on residents and businesses that border these roads it also creates and number of “rat runs”  Meadway is one of these roads, it is also part of the H2 bus route .

Like other areas of London, we know that the South Bank and people who live, work and visit here are adversely affected by ambient air pollution, with concentrations of nitrogen dioxide a particular concern. However, real-time air pollution monitoring in the South Bank has previously been limited to St Thomas’ Hospital. We have therefore commissioned a high-density mini network of eight measurement nodes to give a picture of current pollution levels across a range of locations that reflect the different urban environments found across the South Bank. This will give us great baseline data to help inform future environmental improvement projects.

Belvedere Road is a quiet road but it is regularly used by coaches and tour buses, which have bus stands along it. It is used by a mixture of residents, employees and tourists, with people frequently spending periods of time within Jubilee Gardens which are adjacent to the Belvedere Road node. Thank you to Lambeth Council for hosting the node on their land.

The South Bank Business Improvement District (BID) was set up in 2014 to improve the management of South Bank in the face of increasing footfall and falling public spending. We fund and support several public realm services, including enhanced security, cleaning and litter picking, and help to promote South Bank as a leading visitor destination and as the cultural heart of London. We are a voice for South Bank businesses and provide a wealth of networking opportunities to the organisations in our BID area through event and networking programmes.

The work of South Bank BID is achieved by working in collaboration with others who share our vision for the future prosperity of the South Bank, including South Bank Employers’ Group, South Bank and Waterloo Partnership, the Visitor Management Group, South Bank Marketing and Venues Groups and South Bank Business Watch. South Bank BID is an independent organisation, governed by a Board of Directors drawn from a range of businesses within the BID area and who work to support all our levy paying members and to represent their views.

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
Air on the Green would like to better understand the significance of charcoal burning and other unfiltered particulate emissions from restaurants on air quality and health. The concern is that high levels of particulates in unfiltered restaurant pollution might be putting residents at risk of a range of health impacts, including respiratory and cardiovascular risks. 
 
Legislation passed in 2021 now makes it illegal to emit visible smoke from a chimney. However currently the local council does not act on complaints.
The installation of an air monitoring node in an enclave of student housing, flats and houses protected from road pollution but vulnerable to pollution from charcoal burning in restaurants to both north and south (depending on the direction of the wind) is an interesting opportunity to assess the impact of restaurants on local air quality. 
The node will enable us to gather and disseminate crucial data, which we hope will raise awareness of any effect on public health of charcoal burning, and of the potential to improve air quality by means of filtration. 
If the impact of charcoal burning in restaurants is found to be a significant concern, we hope to use this data to set a precedent for communities across the country affected by the same issue so that we can more effectively campaign to our councils. It is also our hope that a case can be made for a scrappage scheme for extraction ducts that could result in a significant improvement in urban air quality. Such a scrappage scheme would help defuse the tensions that inevitably arise when one group asks another group to spend money on improvements.

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
On Saturday 20th January, Bromley Living Streets installed a new air quality monitor at Elmers End Free Church on Goddard Road. We hope this monitor will make a valuable contribution to better understand air quality in Elmers End, with the measurements available here on the Breathe London website.

The monitor, funded by the Breathe London Community Programme, is Bromley’s fourth node on the Breathe London network following the installation of monitors at the Beckenham Beacon, Bethlem Royal Hospital, Princess Royal University Hospital (PRUH) and Orpington Hospital in mid-2022. Bromley Council also maintains an air quality monitoring station on Harwood Avenue near the Civic Centre, with data available online through the London Air Quality Network.

Bromley Council’s Air Quality Action Plan 2020-2025 identified Elmers End Road as having the highest NO2 concentration in the borough (based on data from diffusion tubes), with an average of 51µg/m³. This exceeds the UK annual average guideline of 40µg/m³ and the WHO annual average guideline of 10µg/m³.

If you are part of a local community or faith group that would be interested in installing an air quality node, please reach out to us at bromleygroup@livingstreets.org.uk. While the Breathe London scheme is not currently offering grants to purchase the monitors, we are looking for alternative funding sources and would love to partner with other local groups.

breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
Our community is in the invisible grip of air pollution. Every breath we take which carries life also bears a toxic burden of air pollution. By monitoring the air we all share, we can illuminate this burden on our community and provide ourselves with the opportunity to mitigate vulnerable residents' exposure to the carcinogenic particles and gases that permeate our air. Improving the air for those who breathe it every hour of every day will also enhance it for those who work and visit our vibrant part of London.

With the Breathe London Node, the Falcon Residents Association and Bloomsbury Air will have access to accurate and regular data on air quality. We hope to use this to:

Raise knowledge and awareness about air pollution specifically in South Camden, encompassing the Holborn and Bloomsbury areas.

Provide residents with access to real-time local monitoring data. This localized data will be more engaging and relevant to the community compared to the broader LAQN (London Air Quality Network) data, which many are disconnected from.

Share the air quality information with the wider Tybalds estate community, including community groups (five in total), local schools (four), churches, mosques, and other relevant local organizations. It is also crucial to involve and engage local businesses in these efforts.

Lobby both local and central government authorities to take stronger action in tackling air pollution, advocating for more effective policies and initiatives.

Promote the necessity for reducing the number of car trips and encouraging active travel among those who are capable of adopting alternative transportation modes. This message will be particularly emphasized with local businesses and institutions, some of which still maintain their own car parks that are frequently utilized.

Work with Bloomsbury institutions to spead the word, including the British Medical Association, University College London, Royal National Institute for the Blind, Wellcome Trust, Great Ormand Street Hospital, Corams Field and Foundation, and the Royal College of Anaesthetists (100 yards away).

Our ultimate goal is to witness a significant reduction in traffic volume within the area, as well as in Central London as a whole.

In early 2024, we completed work on a mixed-tenure, mixed-income development of 36 residential dwellings at Church Grove in Lewisham, that will be permanently affordable and have been partly self-built by a team of dedicated volunteers. breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription:
The Friends of Limehouse are taking a systematic approach towards improving our natural environment, which includes reducing air pollution. 

Air pollution levels in Limehouse are amongst the highest in London and are the highest in LB Tower Hamlets by 30%.  The levels are recorded by an LBTH sensor (No35) located to the west of the Limehouse Link and Rotherhithe tunnel portals, and to the junction of Branch Road with Commercial Road, where excessive traffic congestion is common. 

The new Breathe London sensor is located in Branch Road on the east side of the pollution source where levels are likely to be higher than at the existing sensor due the prevailing westerly wind.

We have provided proposals to the authorities on how traffic congestion and hence pollution might be reduced at its source; and have obtained proposals by specialist consultants for a Green Infrastructure Masterplan, including air pollution reduction at its source and beyond.  The GI Masterplan would provide many other benefits such as active travel, community cohesion and enhanced biodiversity.

The additional sensor now located on Branch Road will be invaluable in providing further evidence for the approval of the measures necessary to reduce air pollution and to monitor subsequent improvements.

There are major disparities in the impacts of air pollution, with low-income communities facing greater health risks due to higher exposure to air pollutants.
Low-income communities bear disproportionate health burdens as they experience higher exposure to air pollutants which negatively impacts immunity and increases the transmission of air-borne respiratory infections.

Funding for long-term initiatives that build meaningful partnerships with communities is needed to solve air pollution-related problems. breathe_listsensors_20250617T201433Z.SiteDescription: Several factors have come together to highlight the importance of understanding the quality of the air we breath in and around Chipping Barnet Foodbank. Firstly, we are a service that supports vulnerable people in our community. Many of our clients have adverse medical conditions and experience poverty. When these factors are combined with poor air quality, we know that this can make for significantly worse health outcomes. Secondly, we are based near one of the larger construction sites in the London Borough of Barnet called The Victoria Quarter. In fact, we used to be based on this site and we now reside a couple of hundred metres up the road. It is estimated that 19% of air pollution in Barnet is caused by construction sites. A third factor is the introduction of the Ultra Low Emission Zone (ULEZ). Barnet has been deeply emersed in the debate about ULEZ and passions run high in the suburb. Considering these factors, we are delighted to have a node which is based just outside the entrance to our hall, and which will accurately capture the life of the foodbank from client footfall to delivery traffic to our small carpark. We plan to use the node as an educational platform for the food bank, the parish, and the local community with a view to monitoring and campaigning for good air quality inside as well as outside

The estate is made up of 67 acres, 500,000 square feet of shops, restaurants, cafes and bars, and capacity for 30,000 workers.  Sustainability has been factored into everything from reusing heritage buildings, promoting energy efficiency, and supporting social and cultural diversity. The estate respects its environment, its past, and its future. In connection to the Environmental, Social and Governance priority area of 'Creating Healthy Spaces', a mini network of six air quality monitoring sensors has been installed to help inform decisions and environmental projects in the future.  Each location was selected to collect information on a range of emission sources and receptors. To further understand air quality across the King's Cross Estate, the partnership with Imperial and Breathe London provides the necessary tools to ensure King's Cross has a comprehensive understanding of the performance and health of the estate.
The canal steps just off Granary square are south-facing and sweep down to Regent's Canal. The steps form a natural theatre ideal for outdoor arts, music recitals, and cinema screenings. In the summer months this space is carpeted in green, creating an ideal spot for visitors and office workers to relax and watch the boats slip by in the sun.

The connection to the canal towpath makes this an ideal stop-off point for barges. Additionally, the proximity to Goods Way allows for the sensor to pick up both the impact from canal boats and the nearby road traffic.

This Node is part of a small network being deployed within Rainham in order to investigate issues with recurring fires at a nearby historical  landfill.  The data from this Node will  ,along with long term existing monitoring close by, be fed into additional analysis being commissioned by London Borough of Havering.   

This Node was previously at CLDP0501 Ingrebourne Links Golf and Country Club on a lamp post in the less used part of their car park but was moved onto a lampost just outside their property due to issues around continued hosting.

This Node is south of the landfill.   Traffic on the road will contribute additional pollution at this new location so may be higher than surrounding Nodes.

This node is part of a small network deployed in and around the Grenfell Tower area.
UK Heath Security Agency (UKHSA) have commissioned a network of six measurement nodes. Data from these nodes and others in the local area will be used to consider and assess local air quality around the site.

This monitoring is a continuation and expansion of monitoring that the UKHSA has been commissioning to understand if there could be a risk to health from emissions from the site.

This node is located on a lamp post 145m NE of the Grenfell Tower site.

UKHSA will continue to summarise monitoring data with reports made available via GOV.UK here: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/environmental-monitoring-following-the-grenfell-tower-fire.
